#compdef asynqmon
# =============================================================================
# asynqmon — Ken Hibino's "Web UI for Asynq task
#          queue" — a Go-implemented HTTP server +
#          embedded React frontend that provides at-
#          a-glance dashboards for the running state
#          of an hibiken/asynq distributed task queue:
#          per-queue active/pending/scheduled/retry/
#          archived/completed task counts, individual
#          task payloads + results, worker-process
#          lists, real-time queue-length charts via
#          Prometheus metrics, and read/write
#          management actions (cancel tasks, archive
#          retries, requeue archived, delete
#          completed).
#          Distinguishing from `asynq` CLI dashboard
#          (`asynq dashboard` text-mode TUI; in
#          corpus as `_asynq`; same data, terminal
#          rendering only), Sidekiq Web (Ruby
#          equivalent for Sidekiq), Bull-board
#          (Node.js equivalent for Bull queue),
#          RabbitMQ Management Plugin (built-in
#          RabbitMQ web UI; AMQP not Redis), and
#          Flower (Celery's web UI; Python only) by:
#            - GO-REDIS FOUNDATION — uses redis/
#              go-redis/v9 v9.0.4 (this is the
#              headline CLI library that CONTINUES
#              Axis 45 on the Go side AND marks the
#              **100-LIBRARY-PER-LANGUAGE LANDMARK**
#              on the Go side; see taxonomy notes
#              below) for all Redis Engine operations.
#              go-redis is by Vladimir Mihailenco
#              (same author as uptrace which we
#              covered in R746 for Axis 39 OTel) +
#              now maintained directly under the
#              github.com/redis/ org as the official
#              Redis-team-endorsed Go client.
#              ~22,000+ stars on the underlying
#              library
#            - ASYNQ INTEGRATION — built on Ken
#              Hibino's hibiken/asynq library
#              (~13,329 stars; the dominant Go async
#              task queue) + asynq/x metrics
#              sub-package; asynqmon reads asynq's
#              Redis data structures directly via
#              asynq.RedisConnOpt connection options
#            - STANDALONE WEB UI — embedded HTML +
#              CSS + JS bundled into the Go binary
#              via go:embed; users get a single-
#              file deployment with no separate
#              static-assets directory required.
#              Listen on `-port 8080` (default) +
#              open browser
#            - REDIS CONNECTION FLAGS — comprehensive
#              support for every Redis topology:
#              * `-redis-addr 127.0.0.1:6379` —
#                standalone Redis (default)
#              * `-redis-cluster-nodes
#                node1:6379,node2:6379,node3:6379`
#                — Redis Cluster (sharded)
#              * `-redis-url
#                redis://user:pass@host:6379/0` —
#                URL form (overrides individual
#                flags)
#              * `-redis-db <N>` — non-default DB
#                number
#              * `-redis-password <pw>` — password
#                auth
#              * `-redis-tls <SNI>` — TLS with SNI
#                hostname validation
#              * `-redis-insecure-tls` — disable
#                TLS cert host checks (testing only)
#            - ENV-VAR FALLBACKS for EVERY FLAG —
#              every command-line flag has an env-
#              var equivalent (PORT, REDIS_ADDR,
#              REDIS_DB, REDIS_PASSWORD, REDIS_TLS,
#              REDIS_URL, REDIS_INSECURE_TLS,
#              REDIS_CLUSTER_NODES, READ_ONLY,
#              MAX_PAYLOAD_LENGTH, MAX_RESULT_LENGTH,
#              ENABLE_METRICS_EXPORTER,
#              PROMETHEUS_ADDR).  Suitable for
#              Kubernetes deployments where flags
#              are awkward but env-vars are first-
#              class
#            - PROMETHEUS METRICS EXPORTER —
#              `-enable-metrics-exporter` activates
#              a Prometheus /metrics endpoint on
#              the web UI's HTTP server, exposing
#              queue-length + processed-count +
#              error-count + latency metrics for
#              Grafana dashboards + alerting rules
#            - PROMETHEUS QUERY BACKEND —
#              `-prometheus-addr http://prometheus:
#              9090` lets asynqmon QUERY a
#              Prometheus server to render TIME-
#              SERIES CHARTS of historical queue
#              metrics within the Web UI (vs just
#              point-in-time Redis state)
#            - READ-ONLY MODE — `-read-only`
#              restricts the Web UI to view-only
#              operations; no task cancellation, no
#              queue deletion, no payload editing.
#              Suitable for production deployments
#              where the Web UI is exposed to a
#              broader audience than the operations
#              team
#            - PAYLOAD + RESULT TRUNCATION — `-max-
#              payload-length 200` + `-max-result-
#              length 200` cap the number of UTF-8
#              characters rendered in payload +
#              result cells; protects the UI from
#              megabyte-scale payloads that would
#              otherwise blow up the rendered DOM
#              and slow the browser
#            - GORILLA/MUX HTTP ROUTING — uses the
#              well-established gorilla/mux router
#              (one of the longest-running Go HTTP
#              routing libraries; battle-tested
#              since 2012)
#            - rs/cors CROSS-ORIGIN — embeds rs/cors
#              for CORS headers; the embedded React
#              UI fetches the JSON API from the
#              same origin but the metrics exporter
#              endpoint may be polled from a
#              different origin Grafana instance
#            - PROTOBUF for INTERNAL ASYNQ DATA —
#              asynq stores task data as Protobuf
#              in Redis; asynqmon decodes via the
#              same proto definitions for consistent
#              rendering across asynqmon + asynq
#              CLI clients
#            - 912+ STARS ON hibiken/asynqmon —
#              backed by Ken Hibino (Google) as the
#              primary author + asynq core
#              maintainer; MIT license; sustained
#              development since 2020
#          Used by: Asynq users wanting a web-based
#          alternative to the bundled `asynq
#          dashboard` TUI, operations teams running
#          Asynq-backed services who need historical
#          queue metrics + Grafana integration,
#          Kubernetes Asynq deployments using env-
#          var-based configuration, and audit-
#          conscious environments using `--read-
#          only` to expose the dashboard to a
#          broader read audience without management-
#          action risk.
#
# Author:  Ken Hibino (hibiken on GitHub; based in
#          Mountain View, CA; Google engineer).
#          Also primary author + maintainer of
#          hibiken/asynq (the underlying Go
#          distributed task queue with ~13,329
#          stars).
# Source:  https://github.com/hibiken/asynqmon
#          https://github.com/hibiken/asynqmon/blob/master/cmd/asynqmon/main.go
#          https://github.com/hibiken/asynqmon/blob/master/go.mod
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `asynqmon -h`
#          shows Go stdlib `flag` package's auto-
#          generated help.  Full deployment
#          documentation in repo README.md +
#          Kubernetes Helm chart examples.
# Library: github.com/redis/go-redis/v9 v9.0.4
#          (Vladimir Mihailenco + Redis team's
#          "Type-safe Redis client for Golang").
#          This is the headline dependency for this
#          completion's axis-45 continuation role
#          AND the marker library for the 100-
#          LIBRARY-PER-LANGUAGE Go landmark; see
#          taxonomy notes below.  Also github.com/
#          hibiken/asynq v0.24.1 (the asynq task
#          queue itself), hibiken/asynq/x for the
#          metrics sub-package, github.com/gorilla/
#          mux v1.8 (HTTP routing), github.com/
#          prometheus/client_golang v1.11
#          (Prometheus metrics), github.com/rs/cors
#          v1.7 (CORS middleware), github.com/
#          spf13/cast v1.5 (env-var type
#          conversion), google.golang.org/protobuf
#          v1.30 (asynq task data deserialization),
#          golang.org/x/sys + golang.org/x/time.
# License: MIT
# Status:  912+ stars on hibiken/asynqmon; active
#          maintenance by Ken Hibino + asynq
#          community.  Released as a single Go
#          binary + a Docker image at hibiken/
#          asynqmon on Docker Hub.
