# WHY redis/go-redis IS A DISTINCTIVE AXIS-45
# CONTINUATION + GO 100-LANDMARK LIBRARY:
#
#   github.com/redis/go-redis by Vladimir Mihailenco
#   (now under the official github.com/redis/ org)
#   is the *dominant* Go Redis client by every
#   metric.  Distinguishing characteristics:
#     1. OFFICIAL REDIS-TEAM ENDORSEMENT — when
#        Vladimir Mihailenco transferred maintenance
#        to the Redis Inc team (2023), go-redis
#        became the canonical Go client.  redigo
#        remains popular for legacy projects but
#        new code should use go-redis
#     2. CLUSTER + SENTINEL + STANDALONE — single
#        client API supports all three Redis
#        topologies; the connection options
#        struct (asynq.RedisConnOpt in asynqmon's
#        case) dispatches to the appropriate
#        underlying client transparently
#     3. RESP2 + RESP3 PROTOCOLS — supports both
#        the legacy RESP2 (Redis 6 and earlier)
#        and modern RESP3 (Redis 6+) with push
#        messages, attribute records, big numbers
#     4. PIPELINE + TRANSACTION SUPPORT — first-
#        class Pipeline + Tx APIs for batched
#        commands; suitable for high-throughput
#        deployments that need to amortize round-
#        trip cost across many commands
#     5. PUB/SUB + STREAMS — full Redis Pub/Sub
#        subscription + Redis Streams (XADD/XREAD/
#        XLEN/XACK) support with consumer groups
#     6. OPENTELEMETRY INSTRUMENTATION — the
#        `extra/redisotel` sub-package provides
#        OTel tracing instrumentation; ties in
#        naturally with the OTel Axis 39 entries
#        (rotel R745, uptrace R746, codemachine
#        R747) — Mihailenco himself is the author
#        of uptrace (R746)
#     7. CONNECTION POOLING — built-in connection
#        pool with configurable idle-timeout +
#        max-conn-age + max-idle-conns; suitable
#        for high-fanout server applications
#     8. ~22,120+ STARS ON redis/go-redis — by far
#        the most-starred Redis client in any
#        language ecosystem covered by this
#        taxonomy
#     9. ECOSYSTEM-DOMINANT — used by asynqmon
#        (this completion), asynq itself, machinery,
#        wal-g, whodb, mayfly-go, and effectively
#        every modern Go application that
#        interacts with Redis
